                    <msContents>
                        <summary> This theological work, entitled ‘<title key="work_180660823"
                                >Cyril</title>’ (<title key="work_180660823">ቄርሎስ</title>
                            <title key="work_180660823">Qērellos</title>) in the Ethiopian
                            tradition, consists of a standard set of writings by <persName
                                key="person_51687951">Cyril of Alexandria</persName> and his
                            contemporary ecclesiastical counterparts including <persName
                                key="person_13110116" role="aqt">Theodotus of Ancyra</persName>, <persName
                                key="" role="aqt">Severus of Synnada</persName>, <persName
                                key="person_89754269" role="aqt">Acacius of Melitene</persName>, <persName
                                key="person_296895961" role="aqt">Juvenal of Jerusalem</persName>, <persName
                                key="person_74242478" role="aqt">Rheginus of Constantina</persName>, <persName
                                key="person_60151776753018011426" role="aqt">Eusebius of Heraclea
                                Pontica</persName>, <persName key="person_ 262855657" role="aqt">Firmus of
                                Caesarea</persName>, <persName key="person_89376925" role="aqt">John of
                                Antioch</persName>, <persName key="person_13651211" role="aqt">Epiphanius of
                                Salamis</persName>, <persName key="person_102329138" role="aqt">Proclus of
                                    Cyzicus</persName>, <persName key="person_171025067" role="aqt">Severian of Gabala</persName>, and
                            <persName key="person_88726043" role="aqt">Gregory of Neocaesarea</persName>. Translated from Greek
                            in the mid-first millennium, this work offers a unique witness to a
                            number of otherwise lost patristic works. Based upon a note on a front
                            flyleaves seeming to pertain to the convent of the Egyptian monk
                                <persName key="">Serapion</persName>, it is most likely that this
                            particular manuscript came from <placeName><origPlace>Egypt</origPlace></placeName>,
                            perhaps originally belonging to an Ethiopian monk resident at one of the
                            monasteries there.</summary>
